.TH "truncate_data_node" 9 "truncate_data_node" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
truncate_data_node \- re-compress/encrypt a truncated data node.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "int" truncate_data_node
.BI "(const struct ubifs_info *c "  ","
.BI "const struct inode *inode "  ","
.BI "unsigned int block "  ","
.BI "struct ubifs_data_node *dn "  ","
.BI "int *new_len "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "c" 12
UBIFS file-system description object
.IP "inode" 12
inode which referes to the data node
.IP "block" 12
data block number
.IP "dn" 12
data node to re-compress
.IP "new_len" 12
new length
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
This function is used when an inode is truncated and the last data node of
the inode has to be re-compressed/encrypted and re-written.
